				<div class="postbody">
				Elbrich,
<br />

<br />
The fact that the US had aided both Iran and Iraq while they warred is well known and documented especially in the Woodward story.  The cold war was on.  Europe needed oil going to market and the Soviets were pressing down on the Middle East threatening to remove the worlds primary supply from the market.
<br />

<br />
The entire region was a fracture zone.
<br />

<br />
It was the duty of NATO to do what it could to make sure that there was no conclusive winner between the two.  If there was, the winner would certainly send their armies into Saudi and Kuwait.  Then the Soviets would either roll in to assist or roll over the rear of the agressor depending on who it was.
<br />

<br />
As it turns out, Sadam was the clear winner and he did turn his armies towards Saudi and occupied all of Kuwait.  The Soviets were already teetering internally. The extension of the war between Iran and Iraq lasted long enough that the Soviet Union was not able to interfere when Iran lost.  Had it happened a couple years earlier...
<br />

<br />
Nice job on lying though your [shazaar23]* to villify the US though.  You have not provided any evidence that the US Helped Sadam use chemical weapons nor any violence against civilians.  One of your refeneces doesnt even come up. Neither of rest allude to this reprehensible falsification.  
<br />

<br />
You have taken some small fact known for 20 years and well justified in the face of the disaster to Europe it deflected; And, you are heaping slander on it hoping that it will give your absurd arguements some validity.
<br />

<br />
Having traded with Sadam does not make the US complicant in his acts of terror (if we in fact did. The only source I give any validity to in your post is the Woodward article, even he has a chip on his shoulder as he tries to find one more deep throat... just one more...).  Sadam is the one that used nerve gas on civilians. No amount of warping of truth and fabrication of lies from you is going to change that.
<br />

<br />
What small truths that remain in your point do NOT stop we Americans from recoiling from what Sadam has done with horror.  How can you even suggest such a thing?
<br />

<br />
###
<br />

<br />
This is a disgusting display:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">However, the USA can't ball about the Ba'ath party putting down the uprising and the terrible loss of life now; <span style="font-weight: bold">because that's exactly what the USA hoped would happen</span> and the reason they refused to help the Shi'ites.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Like we are ghouls hoping that Shiites would be slaughtered.  We didn't finish off Sadam after Kuwait because your favorite teet to suck on, the UN, and the rallies of people using identical propoganda as you are now, bound the US's hands.
<br />

<br />
"We will help but only to remove him from Kuwait and put pressure on him economicly." was what the UN and especially Canada in effect declared.  YOU Elberich, with your arguements and slanderous style are the very voice and personification of those who are responsible for the death of those Shiites.  Their blood is on your allegorically personified hands not on US leadership's, theirs were bound by you.
<br />

<br />
Back then I bound those hands as well.  I had hoped that pressure would bring change.  To insinuate that I or any other american were want to see civilians killed is insane.  Did the Shiite connection to Iran weigh in at all in Clintons decision not to follow up on the call that Bush had made?  It may have been considered but I think that the voices of people like you and me were more well considered.  The connection of Iraqi Shiites to Iranian Shiites could have been nothign more than considered trivia in light of all the other factors that bound Bush's and Clintons from acting.
<br />

<br />
That Shiite blood on your hands is on my hands as well for vocally resisting the removal of Sadam in 1992.  Bush1 had wanted to remove Sadam right there and then and called on Shiites to help.  With the best of intentions, people like you and I, like cowards, turned our backs on an oppressed people rising up against an evil dictator hoping in vain that the people of the West had the same backbone as their leaders.
<br />

<br />
I, for one, could no longer hope for a peaceful resolution with Sadam after what he did following his outing from Kuwait.  I'm suprised you could.
<br />

<br />
The "give peace a chance" chant was a green light to this monster to murder civilians wholesale.
<br />

<br />
9/11 may have never happened if 13 or so years ago we as a world united had made an example of Hussien and had a presence in Iraq to expose and divide terrorist networks.  The only way to travel from Saudi or Jordan to Iran or Afghanistan is through Iraq.
<br />

<br />
###
<br />

<br />
There are many nations that the US has sold munitions to and provided intellegence to that have not used them against civilians... including Canada. Sadam proved himself unable to be trusted with the responsibility.  That is part of what made him a present danger to the US.  It is the defining trait of his character that makes him a terrorist.  He <span style="font-weight: bold">used</span> them.
<br />

<br />
Your point does little but reinforce the fact that the US had accurately identified Saddam as a threat early on and had made prudent decisions to delay the inevitable as long as possible.
<br />

<br />
Sadam trained terrorists.
<br />

<br />
###
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">So, do you think that <span style="font-weight: bold">we</span> should condemn all governments that train quasi military bodies to carry out acts of terrorism in their own countries in order to support political interests that lack legitimacy?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
