You don't?
<br />

<br />
Who is the "we" you are referring to? You do not have the proxy nor rights to speak for anyone but yourself as far as your moral decisions go.
<br />

<br />
I certainly condemn all acts of terror against civilians even by government agencies including here in the US.  We keep our dogs on a pretty short leash.
<br />

<br />
The US as a nation does not have the right to make that judgement <span style="font-weight: bold">except when that amoral behavior is directed towards us or our allies</span>.  Then it become a VERY compelling reason to move forward with great purpose and resolve in order to smash the living [bicrius] out of that [shazar23]hole. First with pressure then with force if pressure fails or meets with violence as on 9/11.
<br />

<br />
Sadam was training terrorists and he was justifying the use of terror against the US.  Is that not enough? For myself, the later (and undisputed as fact) point is enough. Does this not constitute enough for me to say to myself, "This guy is a real and persistant threat to me as a terrorist."
<br />

<br />
###
<br />

<br />
It is clear that you have given up on trying to argue that Sadam was not training terrorists.  He was even if they were just... um... sanctioned (not uniformed) and "primarily" domestic.
<br />

<br />
Are these two together not enough for the US to regard Sadam as a clear and present danger?
<br />

<br />
I am not asking what you would do if you were president.
<br />

<br />
I am not asking for your foetid exhortations on how Americans don't get to "cry" about Sadam since they gave him munitions and intelligence once upon a time.
<br />

<br />
I am not asking for you avoid the point by trapping the US in poorly facaded quixotic moral dillemmas that wind up killing hundreds of thousands with misplaced peace rhetoric.
<br />

<br />
I am not asking for you regress to a prosimian state and start flinging feces when in a poor position... Matter of fact... I am likely to demand some sort of gentlemanly resolution if you ever suggest that the US wanted to kill civilians like the Shiites again just to avoid a direct answer.
<br />

<br />
(12 bottles of Guiness at 13 paces sir.)
<br />

<br />
What I am asking is this:
<br />

<br />
If I interpret Sadam's letter as a justification of terrorism on the US... 
<br />

<br />
(You have stopped short of saying that this is not a valid conclusion though not your own.)
<br />

<br />
If I also believe that he was morally capable of commiting attrocities against civilians specificly in a terrorist fashion and know that he is presently equipped with terrorist means and is possibly preparing the worst...
<br />

<br />
(You have completely dodged the point and I can only conclude that is your acquiescence that he was capable and had trained his people in a very significant ways in terrorist strategies.)
<br />

<br />
Are these two views not enough, from a rational perspective, to have considered Sadam to be a clear and present danger to the US?
<br />

