The key words here that are generally missed and obfuscated with misleading healines are: "...even though the US is not a party to the ICC Statute."
<br />

<br />
The ICJ (or ICC or World Court or The Hague or whatever name it is dodging between this week) WOULD have juristiction in the US over US citizens if the US ratified it.  It would supplant the Supreme Court as having authority over US citizens and make them answerable to whatever law the UN wanted to impose this week now that Ghengis Khan or his contemporary counterpart has 2 pocket judges.
<br />

<br />
The ICJ has more binding power over Nations than the UN itself.  Maybe Iraq, Iran and France need an outside court to keep them from commiting genocide. The US does not; Thanks.
<br />

<br />
###
<br />

<br />
The entire comparison between the ICJ charter and the US Constitution was written specificly to make them seem identical.  They are FAR from it.  The first and most eggrecious of the differences the ICJ has no juries.  But in this comparison there is no mention what-so-ever of this discrepancy and it is HUGE one.
<br />

<br />
Each of those clauses are just words on paper till they are "interpreted".  If the ICJ is ratified by the US, every identical right a US citizen has would be usurped by the World Court and interpretted by them not the Supreme Court.
<br />

<br />
###
<br />

<br />
Lets say Palastinians wanted to sue Israel over their Wall they were building.  By your sources, this would not be possible because the court would not have authority over governments, just individuals.
<br />

<br />
Well as it turns out this very thing is going on.  Palastinians are asking that the ICJ rule against Israel (who has NOT ratified the court) in addition the court is haering testimony that any allies of Israel also be forced to pay restitution to the people of Palastine.
<br />

<br />
They are asking that the court reccomend sanctions against the US and Israel and that the court rule that the UN security council cannot veto the resolution.
<br />

<br />
It seems even though the US and Israel did not sign the convention, the court is still assuming jurisdiction. The case is pure politicing for influance and it is perfect illustration of just how easy it is to manipulate that court.  No matter how it turns out today, how will that court rule tomarrow?
<br />

<br />
I, for one, do not want my rights as a US citizen decided by judges from Tajikistan and Columbia.<br />
